\u003ccode\u003eSTART:STOP\u003c/code\u003e syntax similar to Python\nslicing. This allows you to skip lines at the beginning and/or end of the\n\u003ccode\u003eSTDIN\u003c/code\u003e input you would like \u003ccode\u003ejc\u003c/code\u003e to convert.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSTART\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eSTOP\u003c/code\u003e can be positive or negative integers or blank and allow\nyou to specify how many lines to skip and how many lines to process.\nPositive and blank slices are the most memory efficient. Any negative\nintegers in the slice will use more memory.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eFor example, to skip the first and last line of the following text, you\ncould express the slice in a couple ways:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto\" dir=\"auto\" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content=\"$ cat table.txt\n      ### We want to skip this header ###\n          col1       col2\n          foo        1\n          bar        2\n      ### We want to skip this footer ###\n$ cat table.txt | jc 1:-1 --asciitable\n[{\u0026quot;col1\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;foo\u0026quot;,\u0026quot;col2\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;1\u0026quot;},{\u0026quot;col1\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;bar\u0026quot;,\u0026quot;col2\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;2\u0026quot;}]\n$ cat table.txt | jc 1:4 --asciitable\n[{\u0026quot;col1\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;foo\u0026quot;,\u0026quot;col2\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;1\u0026quot;},{\u0026quot;col1\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;bar\u0026quot;,\u0026quot;col2\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;2\u0026quot;}]\"\u003e\u003cpre\u003e$ cat table.txt\n      \u003cspan class=\"pl-c\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"pl-c\"\u003e#\u003c/span\u003e## We want to skip this header ###\u003c/span\u003e\n          col1       col2\n          foo Slurping works for string parsers that accept a single line of\ninput. (e.g. \u003ccode\u003eurl\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eip-address\u003c/code\u003e) To see a list of parsers that support\nthe \u003ccode\u003e--slurp\u003c/code\u003e option, use \u003ccode\u003ejc -hhh\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eFor example, you can send a file with multiple IP addresses (one per line) to\n\u003ccode\u003ejc\u003c/code\u003e with the \u003ccode\u003e--slurp\u003c/code\u003e option and an array of results will output:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto\" dir=\"auto\" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content=\"$ cat ip-addresses.txt | jc --slurp --ip-address\n[\u0026lt;multiple output objects\u0026gt;]\"\u003e\u003cpre\u003e$ cat ip-addresses.txt \u003cspan class=\"pl-k\"\u003e|\u003c/span\u003e jc --slurp --ip-address\n[\u003cspan class=\"pl-k\"\u003e\u0026lt;\u003c/span\u003emultiple output objects\u003cspan class=\"pl-k\"\u003e\u0026gt;\u003c/span\u003e]\u003c/pre\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eThe magic syntax for \u003ccode\u003e/proc\u003c/code\u003e files automatically supports slurping of multiple\nfiles (no need to use the \u003ccode\u003e--slurp\u003c/code\u003e option). For example, you can convert many\nPID files at once:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto\" dir=\"auto\" class=\"pl-k\"\u003e*\u003c/span\u003e/status\n[\u003cspan class=\"pl-k\"\u003e\u0026lt;\u003c/span\u003emultiple output objects\u003cspan There are some streaming parsers (e.g. \u003ccode\u003els-s\u003c/code\u003e and\n\u003ccode\u003eping-s\u003c/code\u003e) that immediately start processing and outputting the data line-by-line\nas \u003ca href=\"https://jsonlines.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003eJSON Lines\u003c/a\u003e (aka \u003ca href=\"http://ndjson.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003eNDJSON\u003c/a\u003e) while\nit is being received from \u003ccode\u003eSTDIN\u003c/code\u003e. This can significantly reduce the amount of\nmemory required to parse large amounts of command output (e.g. \u003ccode\u003els -lR /\u003c/code\u003e) and\ncan sometimes process the data more quickly. Streaming parsers have slightly\ndifferent behavior than standard parsers as outlined below.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eNote: Streaming parsers cannot be used with the \"magic\" syntax\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"markdown-heading\" dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003ch4 tabindex=\"-1\" class=\"heading-element\" dir=\"auto\"\u003eIgnoring Errors\u003c/h4\u003e\u003ca id=\"user-content-ignoring-errors\" class=\"anchor-element\" aria-label=\"Permalink: Ignoring Errors\" href=\"#ignoring-errors\"\u003e\u003csvg class=\"octicon octicon-link\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eYou may want to ignore parsing errors when using streaming parsers since these\nmay be used in long-lived processing pipelines and errors can break the pipe. To\nignore parsing errors, use the \u003ccode\u003e-qq\u003c/code\u003e cli option or the \u003ccode\u003eignore_exceptions=True\u003c/code\u003e\nargument with the \u003ccode\u003eparse()\u003c/code\u003e function. This will add a \u003ccode\u003e_jc_meta\u003c/code\u003e object to the\nJSON output with a \u003ccode\u003esuccess\u003c/code\u003e attribute. dir=\"auto\"\u003eMost operating systems will buffer output that is being piped from process to\nprocess. The buffer is usually around 4KB. When viewing the output in the\nterminal the OS buffer is not engaged so output is immediately displayed on the\nscreen. When piping multiple processes together, though, it may seem as if the\noutput is hanging when the input data is very slow (e.g. \u003ccode\u003eping\u003c/code\u003e):\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto\" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content=\"$ ping 1.1.1.1 | jc --ping-s | jq\n\u0026lt;slow output\u0026gt;\"\u003e\u003cpre class=\"notranslate\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$ ping 1.1.1.1 | jc --ping-s | jq\n\u0026lt;slow output\u0026gt;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eThis is because the OS engages the 4KB buffer between \u003ccode\u003ejc\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ejq\u003c/code\u003e in this\nexample. To display the data on the terminal in realtime, you can disable the\nbuffer with the \u003ccode\u003e-u\u003c/code\u003e (unbuffer) cli option:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto\" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content=\"$ ping 1.1.1.1 | jc --ping-s -u | jq\n{\u0026quot;type\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;reply\u0026quot;,\u0026quot;pattern\u0026quot;:null,\u0026quot;timestamp\u0026quot;:null,\u0026quot;bytes\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;64\u0026quot;,\u0026quot;respons...}\n{\u0026quot;type\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;reply\u0026quot;,\u0026quot;pattern\u0026quot;:null,\u0026quot;timestamp\u0026quot;:null,\u0026quot;bytes\u0026quot;:\u0026quot;64\u0026quot;,\u0026quot;respons...}\n...\"\u003e\u003cpre class=\"notranslate\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$ ping 1.1.1.1 | jc --ping-s -u | jq\n{\"type\":\"reply\",\"pattern\":null,\"timestamp\":null,\"bytes\":\"64\",\"respons...}\n{\"type\":\"reply\",\"pattern\":null,\"timestamp\":null,\"bytes\":\"64\",\"respons...}\n...\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp This allows you to skip lines at the beginning and/or end of the<code>STDIN</code> input you would like <code>jc</code> to convert.</p><p dir="auto"><code>START</code> and <code>STOP</code> can be positive or negative integers or blank and allowyou to specify how many lines to skip and how many lines to process.Positive and blank slices are the most memory efficient. Any negativeintegers in the slice will use more memory.</p><p dir="auto">For example, to skip the first and last line of the following text, youcould express the slice in a couple ways:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="$ cat table.txt      ### We want to skip this header ###          col1       col2          foo        1          bar        2      ### We want to skip this footer ###$ cat table.txt | jc 1:-1 --asciitable[{"col1":"foo","col2":"1"},{"col1":"bar","col2":"2"}]$ cat table.txt | jc 1:4 --asciitable[{"col1":"foo","col2":"1"},{"col1":"bar","col2":"2"}]"><pre>$ cat table.txt      <span class="pl-c"><span class="pl-c">#</span>## We want to skip this header ###</span>          col1       col2          foo        1          bar        2      <span class="pl-c"><span class="pl-c">#</span>## We want to skip this footer ###</span>$ cat table.txt <span class="pl-k">|</span> jc 1:-1 --asciitable[{<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>col1<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>:<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>foo<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>col2<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>:<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>1<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>},{<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>col1<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>:<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>bar<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>col2<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>:<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>2<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>}]$ cat table.txt <span class="pl-k">|</span> jc 1:4 --asciitable[{<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>col1<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>:<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>foo<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>col2<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>:<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>1<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>},{<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>col1<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>:<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>bar<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>col2<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>:<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>2<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>}]</pre></div><p dir="auto">In this example <code>1:-1</code> and <code>1:4</code> line slices provide the same output.</p><p dir="auto">When using positive integers the index location of <code>STOP</code> is non-inclusive.Positive slices count from the first line of the input toward the endstarting at <code>0</code> as the first line. Negative slices count from the last linetoward the beginning starting at <code>-1</code> as the last line. This is also the way<a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/509211/understanding-slicing" rel="nofollow">Python's slicing</a>feature works.</p><p dir="auto">Here is a breakdown of line slice options:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Slice Notation</th><th>Input Lines Processed</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>START:STOP</code></td><td>lines <code>START</code> through <code>STOP - 1</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>START:</code></td><td>lines <code>START</code> through the rest of the output</td></tr><tr><td><code>:STOP</code></td><td>lines from the beginning through <code>STOP - 1</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>-START:STOP</code></td><td><code>START</code> lines from the end through <code>STOP - 1</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>START:-STOP</code></td><td>lines <code>START</code> through <code>STOP</code> lines from the end</td></tr><tr><td><code>-START:-STOP</code></td><td><code>START</code> lines from the end through <code>STOP</code> lines from the end</td></tr><tr><td><code>-START:</code></td><td><code>START</code> lines from the end through the rest of the output</td></tr><tr><td><code>:-STOP</code></td><td>lines from the beginning through <code>STOP</code> lines from the end</td></tr><tr><td><code>:</code></td><td>all lines</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Slurp</h3><a id="user-content-slurp" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Slurp" href="#slurp"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">Some parsers support multi-item input and can output an array of results in asingle pass. Slurping works for string parsers that accept a single line ofinput. (e.g. <code>url</code> and <code>ip-address</code>) To see a list of parsers that supportthe <code>--slurp</code> option, use <code>jc -hhh</code>.</p><p dir="auto">For example, you can send a file with multiple IP addresses (one per line) to<code>jc</code> with the <code>--slurp</code> option and an array of results will output:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="$ cat ip-addresses.txt | jc --slurp --ip-address[<multiple output objects>]"><pre>$ cat ip-addresses.txt <span class="pl-k">|</span> jc --slurp --ip-address[<span class="pl-k"><</span>multiple output objects<span class="pl-k">></span>]</pre></div><p dir="auto">The magic syntax for <code>/proc</code> files automatically supports slurping of multiplefiles (no need to use the <code>--slurp</code> option). For example, you can convert manyPID files at once:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="$ jc /proc/*/status[<multiple output objects>]"><pre>$ jc /proc/<span class="pl-k">*</span>/status[<span class="pl-k"><</span>multiple output objects<span class="pl-k">></span>]</pre></div><p dir="auto">When the <code>/proc</code> magic syntax is used and multiple files are selected, anadditional <code>_file</code> field is inserted in the output so it is easier to tell whatfile each output object refers to.</p><p dir="auto">Finally, the <code>--meta-out</code> option can be used in conjunction with slurped output.In this case, the slurped output is wrapped in an object with the followingstructure:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-json notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="{  "result": [<multiple output objects>],  "_jc_meta": {    "parser": "url",    "timestamp": 1706235558.654576,    "slice_start": null,    "slice_end": null,    "input_list": [      "http://www.google.com",      "https://www.apple.com",      "https://www.microsoft.com"    ]  }}"><pre>{  <span class="pl-ent">"result"</span>: [<span class="pl-ii"><multiple output objects></span>],  <span class="pl-ent">"_jc_meta"</span>: {    <span class="pl-ent">"parser"</span>: <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>url<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,    <span class="pl-ent">"timestamp"</span>: <span class="pl-c1">1706235558.654576</span>,    <span class="pl-ent">"slice_start"</span>: <span class="pl-c1">null</span>,    <span class="pl-ent">"slice_end"</span>: <span class="pl-c1">null</span>,    <span class="pl-ent">"input_list"</span>: [      <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>http://www.google.com<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,      <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>https://www.apple.com<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,      <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>https://www.microsoft.com<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>    ]  }}</pre></div><p dir="auto">With <code>--meta-out</code>, <code>input_list</code> contains a list of inputs (actual input stringsor <code>/proc</code> filenames) so you can identify which output object relates to eachinput string or <code>/proc</code> filename.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Exit Codes</h3><a id="user-content-exit-codes" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Exit Codes" href="#exit-codes"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">Any fatal errors within <code>jc</code> will generate an exit code of <code>100</code>, otherwise theexit code will be <code>0</code>.</p><p dir="auto">When using the "magic" syntax (e.g. <code>jc ifconfig eth0</code>),<code>jc</code> will store the exit code of the program being parsed and add it to the <code>jc</code>exit code. This way it is easier to determine if an error was from the parsedprogram or <code>jc</code>.</p><p dir="auto">Consider the following examples using <code>ifconfig</code>:</p><table><thead><tr><th><code>ifconfig</code> exit code</th><th><code>jc</code> exit code</th><th>Combined exit code</th><th>Interpretation</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>0</code></td><td><code>0</code></td><td><code>0</code></td><td>No errors</td></tr><tr><td><code>1</code></td><td><code>0</code></td><td><code>1</code></td><td>Error in  <code>ifconfig</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>0</code></td><td><code>100</code></td><td><code>100</code></td><td>Error in  <code>jc</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>1</code></td><td><code>100</code></td><td><code>101</code></td><td>Error in  both <code>ifconfig</code> and <code>jc</code></td></tr></tbody></table><p dir="auto">When using the "magic" syntax you can also retrieve the exit code of the calledprogram by using the <code>--meta-out</code> or <code>-M</code> option. This will append a <code>_jc_meta</code>object to the output that will include the magic command information, includingthe exit code.</p><p dir="auto">Here is an example with <code>ping</code>:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="$ jc --meta-out -p ping -c2 class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>ping<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,    <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>timestamp<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>: 1661357115.27949, Note that using the <code>-C</code> option to forcecolor output will override both the <code>NO_COLOR</code> environment variable and the <code>-m</code>option.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h3 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Streaming Parsers</h3><a id="user-content-streaming-parsers" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Streaming Parsers" href="#streaming-parsers"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">Most parsers load all of the data from <code>STDIN</code>, parse it, then output the entireJSON document serially. There are some streaming parsers (e.g. <code>ls-s</code> and<code>ping-s</code>) that immediately start processing and outputting the data line-by-lineas <a href="https://jsonlines.org/" rel="nofollow">JSON Lines</a> (aka <a href="http://ndjson.org/" rel="nofollow">NDJSON</a>) whileit is being received from <code>STDIN</code>. This can significantly reduce the amount ofmemory required to parse large amounts of command output (e.g. <code>ls -lR /</code>) andcan sometimes process the data more quickly. Streaming parsers have slightlydifferent behavior than standard parsers as outlined below.</p><blockquote><p dir="auto">Note: Streaming parsers cannot be used with the "magic" syntax</p></blockquote><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h4 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Ignoring Errors</h4><a id="user-content-ignoring-errors" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Ignoring Errors" href="#ignoring-errors"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">You may want to ignore parsing errors when using streaming parsers since thesemay be used in long-lived processing pipelines and errors can break the pipe. Toignore parsing errors, use the <code>-qq</code> cli option or the <code>ignore_exceptions=True</code>argument with the <code>parse()</code> function. This will add a <code>_jc_meta</code> object to theJSON output with a <code>success</code> attribute. If <code>success</code> is <code>true</code>, then there wereno issues parsing the line. If <code>success</code> is <code>false</code>, then a parsing issue wasfound and <code>error</code> and <code>line</code> fields will be added to include a short errordescription and the contents of the unparsable line, respectively:</p><p dir="auto">Successfully parsed line with <code>-qq</code> option:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-json notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="{  "command_data": "data",  "_jc_meta": {    "success": true  }}"><pre>{  <span class="pl-ent">"command_data"</span>: <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>data<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,  <span class="pl-ent">"_jc_meta"</span>: {    <span class="pl-ent">"success"</span>: <span class="pl-c1">true</span>  }}</pre></div><p data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="{  "_jc_meta": {    "success": false,    "error": "error message",    "line": "original line data"  }}"><pre>{  <span class="pl-ent">"_jc_meta"</span>: {    <span class="pl-ent">"success"</span>: <span class="pl-c1">false</span>,    <span class="pl-ent">"error"</span>: <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>error message<span process toprocess. The buffer is usually around 4KB. When viewing the output in theterminal the OS buffer is not engaged so output is immediately displayed on thescreen. When piping multiple processes together, though, it may seem as if theoutput is hanging when the input data is very slow (e.g. <code>ping</code>):</p><div class="snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="$ ping 1.1.1.1 | jc --ping-s | jq<slow output>"><pre class="notranslate"><code>$ ping 1.1.1.1 | jc --ping-s | jq<slow output></code></pre></div><p dir="auto">This is because the OS engages the 4KB buffer between <code>jc</code> and <code>jq</code> in thisexample. To display the data on the terminal in realtime, you can disable thebuffer with the <code>-u</code> (unbuffer) cli option:</p><div class="snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="$ ping 1.1.1.1 | jc --ping-s -u | jq{"type":"reply","pattern":null,"timestamp":null,"bytes":"64","respons...}{"type":"reply","pattern":null,"timestamp":null,"bytes":"64","respons...}..."><pre class="notranslate"><code>$ ping 1.1.1.1 | jc --ping-s -u | jq{"type":"reply","pattern":null,"timestamp":null,"bytes":"64","respons...}{"type":"reply","pattern":null,"timestamp":null,"bytes":"64","respons...}...</code></pre></div><blockquote><p dir="auto">Note: Unbuffered output can be slower for large data streams.</p></blockquote><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h4 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Using Streaming Parsers as Python Modules</h4><a id="user-content-using-streaming-parsers-as-python-modules" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Using Streaming Parsers as Python Modules" href="#using-streaming-parsers-as-python-modules"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">Streaming parsers accept any iterable object and return an iterable objectallowing lazy processing of the data. The input data should iterate on linesof string data. Examples of good input data are <code>sys.stdin</code> or<code>str.splitlines()</code>.</p><p dir="auto">To use the returned iterable object in your code, simply loop through it oruse the <a href="https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#next" rel="nofollow">next()</a>builtin function:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-python notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="import jcresult = jc.parse('ls_s', ls_command_output.splitlines())for item in result:    print(item["filename"])"><pre><span class="pl-k">import</span> <span class="pl-s1">jc</span><span class="pl-s1">result</span> <span class="pl-c1">=</span> <span class="pl-s1">jc</span>.<span class="pl-en">parse</span>(<span class="pl-s">'ls_s'</span>, <span dir="auto"><li>Linux/unix: <code>$HOME/.local/share/jc/jcparsers</code></li><li>macOS: <code>$HOME/Library/Application Support/jc/jcparsers</code></li><li>Windows: <code>$LOCALAPPDATA\jc\jc\jcparsers</code></li></ul><p dir="auto">Parser plugins are standard python module files. Use the<a href="https://github.com/kellyjonbrazil/jc/blob/master/jc/parsers/foo.py"><code>jc/parsers/foo.py</code></a>or <a href="https://github.com/kellyjonbrazil/jc/blob/master/jc/parsers/foo_s.py"><code>jc/parsers/foo_s.py (streaming)</code></a>parser as a template and simply place a <code>.py</code> file in the <code>jcparsers</code> subfolder.Any dependencies can be placed in the <code>jc</code> folder above <code>jcparsers</code> and canbe imported in the parser code.</p><p dir="auto">Parser plugin filenames must be valid python module names and therefore muststart with a letter and consist entirely of alphanumerics and underscores.Local plugins may override default parsers.</p><blockquote><p Unlessa timestamp field name has a <code>_utc</code> suffix it is considered naive. (i.e. basedon the local timezone of the system the <code>jc</code> parser was run on).</p><p dir="auto">If a UTC timezone can be detected in the text of the command output, thetimestamp will be timezone aware and have a <code>_utc</code> suffix on the key name.(e.g. <code>epoch_utc</code>) No other timezones are supported for aware timestamps.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Use In Other Shells</h2><a id="user-content-use-in-other-shells" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Use In Other Shells" href="#use-in-other-shells"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto"><code>jc</code> can be used in most any shell.
